+# Maintenance Mode Security Comparison
+
+Quick reference for choosing the right maintenance mode strategy.
+
+## üî¥ INSECURE (Never use in production)
+
+### Frontend Environment Variable
+```bash
+VITE_MAINTENANCE_BYPASS_TOKEN="secret123"
+```
+
+**Why insecure:**
+- Token visible in compiled JavaScript
+- Anyone can view: `console.log(import.meta.env.VITE_MAINTENANCE_BYPASS_TOKEN)`
+- Cannot revoke without rebuild
+- Exposed in browser DevTools
+
+**Use case:** Development/staging only
+
+---
+
+## üü° MEDIUM SECURITY (OK for internal use)
+
+### HTTP Basic Auth
+
+```nginx
+# Nginx configuration
+location / {
+  auth_basic "Maintenance Access";
+  auth_basic_user_file /etc/nginx/.htpasswd;
+}
+```
+
+**Pros:**
+- Built into browsers
+- Simple to implement
+- No custom code needed
+
+**Cons:**
+- Password shared among team
+- Not ideal for dynamic control
+
+**Use case:** Small teams, scheduled maintenance
+
+---
+
+## üü¢ SECURE (Production-ready)
+
+### 1. Backend Token Verification ‚≠ê Recommended
+
+**How it works:**
+1. Token stored ONLY in backend environment
+2. Frontend sends token to API
+3. Backend validates and sets session cookie
+
+**Implementation:**
+```javascript
+// Frontend (no token exposed)
+const response = await fetch('/api/maintenance/verify', {
+  method: 'POST',
+  body: JSON.stringify({ token: userInputToken }),
+})
+
+// Backend validates
+if (token === process.env.SECRET_TOKEN) {
+  req.session.bypass = true
+}
+```
+
+**Pros:**
+- Token never exposed to client
+- Can revoke instantly (clear sessions)
+- Supports time-limited tokens
+- Centralized control
+
+**Cons:**
+- Requires backend endpoint
+- More complex setup
+
+**Files:**
+- `src/router/maintenanceGuard.secure.js`
+- `cms/src/endpoints/maintenance.example.ts`
+
+---
+
+### 2. IP Allowlist (CDN Level)
+
+**Cloudflare Example:**
+```javascript
+// Cloudflare Worker
+const allowedIPs = ['203.0.113.1', '198.51.100.0/24']
+
+if (maintenanceMode && !allowedIPs.includes(clientIP)) {
+  return new Response('Maintenance', { status: 503 })
+}
+```
+
+**Pros:**
+- No tokens needed
+- Instant activation
+- Cannot be bypassed by users
+
+**Cons:**
+- Requires static IPs
+- Less flexible (IP changes = locked out)
+
+**Best for:** Office networks, VPN users
+
+---
+
+### 3. Cloudflare Access (Enterprise-grade)
+
+**Setup:**
+1. Enable Cloudflare Access
+2. Create application rule
+3. Add allowed emails/domains
+
+**Pros:**
+- Enterprise SSO support
+- Multi-factor authentication
+- Audit logs included
+- Free tier available
+
+**Cons:**
+- Requires Cloudflare
+- More complex setup
+
+**Best for:** Large teams, compliance requirements
+
+---
+
+## Quick Decision Matrix
+
+| Scenario | Recommended Method | Security Level |
+|----------|-------------------|----------------|
+| Local development | Frontend env var | üî¥ Low (OK) |
+| Staging server | HTTP Basic Auth | üü° Medium |
+| Production (small team) | IP Allowlist | üü¢ High |
+| Production (dynamic) | Backend verification | üü¢ High |
+| Enterprise | Cloudflare Access | üü¢ Very High |
+
+---
+
+## Implementation Priority
+
+### Phase 1: Development (Current)
+‚úÖ Basic frontend token
+- Fast to implement
+- Good for testing
+- **Don't use in production**
+
+### Phase 2: Production Launch
+Choose ONE:
+1. **Backend verification** (most flexible)
+2. **IP allowlist** (simplest if you have static IPs)
+3. **HTTP Basic Auth** (quick win)
+
+### Phase 3: Scale (Optional)
+- Cloudflare Access for team growth
+- Session management
+- Audit logging
+
